topic.body:
I'm continuing on the track of trying to figure out how to use databases within zeronet. There seems to be little information aside from a singular example of a dbschema.json file with brief explanation and no other sources.

I've noticed in a ZeroChat tutorial that you can use a SELECT statement (using SQL from a dbquery function) so decided to see if ZeroNet can use SQL fully. My first test involves trying a simple UPDATE string:

"UPDATE json SET access=1 WHERE json_id=1"

I'm using the same site made from the ZeroChat tutorial:
http://127.0.0.1:43110/Blog.ZeroNetwork.bit/?Post:99:ZeroChat+tutorial

It unfortunately doesn't seem to have any affect (the access value remains null, so not even an integer). This the dbschema.json that i've used to build the database:

{
    "db_name": "ZeroChat",
    "db_file": "data/zerochat.db",
    "version": 2,
    "maps": {
        "users/.+/data.json": {
            "to_table": [ "message" ]
        },
        "users/.+/content.json": {
            "to_json_table": [ "cert_user_id" ],
            "file_name": "data.json"
        }
    },
    "tables": {
        "json": {
            "cols": [
                ["json_id", "INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT"],
				["access", "INTEGER"],
                ["directory", "TEXT"],
                ["file_name", "TEXT"],
                ["cert_user_id", "TEXT"]
            ],
            "indexes": ["CREATE UNIQUE INDEX path ON json(directory, file_name)"],
            "schema_changed": 10
        },
        "message": {
            "cols": [
                ["body", "TEXT"],
                ["date_added", "INTEGER"],
                ["json_id", "INTEGER REFERENCES json (json_id)"]
            ],
            "indexes": ["CREATE UNIQUE INDEX message_key ON message(json_id, date_added)"],
            "schema_changed": 10
        }
    }
}

1520304150_1J6csQA9K9NZaYUiCG5C2XQRF85yB.body:
I may have figured it out, though it will take some time to fix.

This is from the index.js:
	postAdd.onclick = function() {
		addPost(function(id) {
			location.href = "edit.html?" + id;
		});
	};

When an admin clicks the add post button on the main index.html page, it automatically runs addPost() which creates a blank post and saves it to the file (finalizing the changes). This doesn't answer the problem of how a blank post gets filled with values from the edit form, but this does show that even when pressing back/cancel that a blank post at the very least is being added and saved to the json file.

Will be working on this further, thank you guys for the patience/help.
